This paper is about using evolutionary and individual learning methods to adapt a robotic swarm in potentially unknown environments. The focus is on the performance of the swarm in dynamic environments, which suggests a robotics (RO) sub-category. The use of evolutionary algorithms and individual learning mechanisms also suggests artificial intelligence (AI) and machine learning (MA) sub-categories. The fact that the swarm is distributed and operates for long periods suggests a systems and control (SY) sub-category. Finally, the use of parameters that can be fixed or inherited suggests a potential focus on optimization and learning (LG) sub-category.
